Puntland was recently named the most stable state in Somalia by the London-based think-tank, International Crisis Group.

Mr Abdirahman's remarks come after Mogadishu and other parts of the country were hit by heavy rains and flash floods.

Many in the city have complained that they were left to fend for themselves as the authorities were slow to respond to the floods.

"They have never come to help the people. They came here today because the cameras are here," said one resident.

"You can see the children and women standing in the water, it's cold, it's windy and they have nothing to protect them. We don't have a leader who looks after us," he added.

This was the second time in three years that the city has been affected by heavy rains, with thousands displaced in 2017.

"We have done our best, but the magnitude of the disaster is beyond the city's capacity," said Mogadishu mayor Omar Mohamud Mohamed (Filish).

The mayor's comments came even as some of the displaced people were camping in the open as they were yet to be evacuated.

The United Nations on Monday warned that the floods were increasing the risk of diseases such as cholera and malaria.

"The displaced people need urgent assistance, especially women and children, who are sleeping outside in the cold and rainy weather," said Mr Adam Abdelmoula, the UN resident and humanitarian coordinator for Somalia.

"We are in an emergency mode. We are calling on the international community to come forward and support these people with shelter, food, health and nutrition," he added

He died before the sun set. He was only thirty-five years old.

At first we did not know what to do with the bodies. We placed them in the front rooms of our houses, waiting for them to be taken away. But nobody came. And the dead kept piling up.

It was then that we decided to bury our dead. But we were all afraid. We had never seen such a thing before. When we touched the dead bodies we felt cold, like ice. We washed them, put on their shrouds, carried them on stretchers and buried them.

But the bodies did not decompose. They remained as if they were alive. The limbs did not stiffen. The eyes were not clouded over. The skin did not turn blue or black.

At first we were horrified. We thought that the dead were being punished. We believed that they had not died properly. We did not know what to do. We were afraid to go near them.

The bodies did not rot for many months. They became harder and harder. They were like logs of wood. We were terrified to touch them. They became our own dead. We could not bear to look at them.

I have a lot of favorite stories about visits from spirits, but this one really stands out. I like this story because of the comfort and reassurance I got from the ghost of my grandmother.

I was about 8 years old. It was a very cold night and I had been crying. My grandmother had died a few months before, and I missed her very much. I was really missing her that night. I was crying and my mother was upset. She had tried to comfort me, but I was inconsolable. She put me to bed, but I was still crying and asking to go downstairs.

I was in bed, crying, when I heard the front door open. I looked out of my bedroom window and saw my grandmother walking up the path to the house. I saw her, plain as day, in a long coat, coming up the path. I heard the door open and close again. She came into the bedroom and stood beside my bed. She didn't say anything, but she was smiling. I smiled back, and felt so happy and at peace. She just stood there for a while, then she walked out of the room.

I lay in bed, and I was no longer crying. I was calm, and I felt so happy and peaceful. I don't know how long she stayed, but I remember lying there, thinking about how happy I was. I knew she was there for me. I knew she was there to help me, and that she would always be there. I fell asleep, feeling so much better.

This is my favorite story, because it happened to me, and it made me feel better. It made me feel happy and loved.

I am so glad I had the opportunity to tell my story, and I hope you enjoyed reading it. Thank you for your time, and I hope you have a good day.

Please let me know if you have any questions or comments, and I will be happy to answer them. Thank you again.
